                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support> CPAT Regional Historic Environment Record: <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/"><idno type="HER">928</idno>Ystrad</ref>
                                    <material>Sandstone</material> <objectType>pillar</objectType>, described as <q>pale grey, darker-grey weathering, coarse-grained sandstone...considered to be locally derived</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 177-8).
                                    <dimensions unit="m" source="RED2007">
                                        <height>1.20</height>
                                        <width>0.38</width>
                                        <depth>0.36</depth></dimensions></support>
                                <condition>Badly weathered, the outline of the characters rounded and some completely obliterated (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 178).</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The stone is inscribed with a worn Ogham inscription along the left-hand edge reading vertically upwards. In addition to the Ogham inscription, Webley described detecting a series of weathered horizontal lines potentially representing a Latin inscription which today is illegible(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 178; Webley 1957, 118-21).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The inscription is <rs type="execution" key="carved" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/168.html"> carved</rs>. The vowels in the inscription have largely worn away but the spaces between the legible characters suggest their original presence(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 178).
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
