            <div type="commentary">
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1">
                        <p>The Ogham inscription is probably a commemorative formula, naming an individual with the popular Irish name <hi rend="italic">*Makʷkʷas-Dekantos</hi> 'son of [the divinity] Dekans', which is also found elsewhere in Britain as <hi rend="italic">CIIC:</hi> no. 326; <hi rend="italic">CIIC:</hi> no. 429; <hi rend="italic">CIIC:</hi> no. 440. The Welsh Corpus notes that <q>in these other forms the genitive ending -I has been rounded to U or O by the preceding labiovelar /kʷ/</q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 178). It is uncertain whether that is the case for this inscription, due to its worn nature, but the Welsh Corpus argues for the ending [I]. (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 178).</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
